\begin_layout Standard
As an advanced example of using the relational parametricity theorem, we
 will now show that for certain type constructors 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

, one can simplify a function type 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall A.\,P^{A}\rightarrow Q^{A}+R^{A}$
\end_inset

 into a disjunctive type 
\begin_inset Formula $(\forall A.\,P^{A}\rightarrow Q^{A})+(\forall A.\,P^{A}\rightarrow R^{A})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Generally, the type expression 
\begin_inset Formula $P\rightarrow Q+R$
\end_inset

 is not equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $(P\rightarrow Q)+(P\rightarrow R)$
\end_inset

.
 However, the situation becomes different once we assume full parametricity
 and impose a universal quantifier.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a first example, consider a fully parametric function 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 of type:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k:\forall A.\,A\rightarrow\bbnum 1+A\quad.
\]

\end_inset

The function 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 must construct a value of type 
\begin_inset Formula $\bbnum 1+A$
\end_inset

 given a value of type 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 So, the code of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 must decide to return either the first or the second part of the disjunctive
 type 
\begin_inset Formula $\bbnum 1+A$
\end_inset

.
 That decision 
\emph on
cannot
\emph default
 depend on the value of the input argument (of type 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

) because nothing is known about the type 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, the code of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 cannot perform any pattern-matching on the input argument.
 It follows that the decision about the disjunctive return value must be
 hard-coded: for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 the value 
\begin_inset Formula $k(x)$
\end_inset

 must be 
\begin_inset Formula $1+\bbnum 0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, and for other functions 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 the value 
\begin_inset Formula $k(x)$
\end_inset

 must be 
\begin_inset Formula $\bbnum 0+x$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 So, the fully parametric type 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall A.\,A\rightarrow\bbnum 1+A$
\end_inset

 splits into a disjunction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall A.\,A\rightarrow\bbnum 1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall A.\,A\rightarrow A$
\end_inset

.
 Each of those types has only one possible implementation:
\begin_inset listings
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

